<HEADLINE> Women Urged to Form Economic Blocs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Women should organize themselves
into strong economic entities in the informal sector, Zimbabwe's
first lady Grace Mugabe said here today.
</P>
<P>
Officially closing the eighth Pan African Women's Organization
(PAWO) Congress, Mrs. Mugabe said women should venture into these
because it is difficult for them to undertake large enterprises
under the current economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
Much still needed to be done to improve the economic status of
women in Africa, she said, adding that governments should support
small-scale economic activities such as markets.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Mugabe also urged women to seek assistance to improve
their management skills so that they could run their undertakings
efficiently.
</P>
<P>
''Indeed, when women are safe and secure economically, they
can contribute immensely to solving some of our social ills,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
The first lady said the resolutions made at the congress would
have far-reaching implications especially in the areas of
education, economy and culture.
</P>
<P>
''Educated girl children are certainly a positive assurance
for our continent's prosperity,'' she said, adding that women
should assist in the preservation of African culture.
</P>
<P>
The congress, which started on July 28, discussed issues
pertaining to women and focused on poverty, education, violence,
economic empowerment and status of women.
</P>
<P>
The PAWO, formed by women in 1962 to fight against
colonialism, has now shifted its focus on regional conflicts.
</P>
</TEXT>
