<HEADLINE> World Wheat Supply, Demand in 1997/98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- World wheat production is forecast
6 million higher at 585 million tons in 1997/98, compared with 582
million tons in 1996/97, according to a press release by the
International Grains Council today.
</P>
<P>
The main changes from last month include higher estimates for
the United States, Russia, China and Pakistan, but reductions for
the European Community, Central/Eastern Europe and North Africa.
</P>
<P>
World wheat trade is now forecast 1 million higher at 96
million tons, 2 million more than last year and the highest since
1992/93.
</P>
<P>
The latest data include increases for Poland, Iran, Pakistan
and Egypt, offsetting reductions for China and India.
</P>
<P>
With regard to exporting countries, a lower figure for
Australia is compensated by increases for Argentina and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
While projected exports are unchanged for Hungary and Romania,
supplies from these origins could include substantial amounts of
feed quality wheat.
</P>
<P>
World wheat consumption is forecast 2 million higher at 584
million tons, compared with 587 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
The figure for food use is unchanged at 434 million tons. Feed
use has been raised by 2 million to 94 million tons, reflecting an
increase in the United States and a small recovery in Russia in
line with a larger harvest.
</P>
<P>
World wheat stocks are forecast 1 million tons up on last
season's revised total at 100 million tons. Amongst the major
exporters, stocks in the United States will increase, Canada will
record a decline, and those in Argentina, Australia and the EC
could be little changed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
