<HEADLINE> New Treatment Increases Prostate Cancer Survival Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A combination of radiation therapy
and a hormone treatment can significantly increase the survival
rate of men with prostate cancer that has begun to spread, a joint
Canadian and European study has found.
</P>
<P>
The study followed a group of men who were treated after their
advanced cancer had spread outside the prostate but before it had
begun to form tumors in other organs of the body.
</P>
<P>
Those who received a hormone treatment after radiation had a
five-year survival rate of 17 percentage points higher than those
who received the standard radiation treatment alone.
</P>
<P>
In effect, the synthetic hormone shuts down production of the
male sex hormone testosterone, to prevent testosterone from
stimulating growth for cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
The side effects are losing interest in sex and hot flashes,
the study said. The results appear today in the New England
Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
The eight-year study involved 415 men, who were randomly
assigned to two treatment groups, one receiving seven weeks of
radiation treatment alone and the second receiving radiation plus
a hormone taken over three years.
</P>
<P>
After five years, 79 percent of the men in the first group were
still alive, compared with 62 percent of the second group.
</P>
<P>
And about 85 percent of the survivors in the combined therapy
group and only 48 percent of those who had radiation alone did not
have a recurrence of their cancer.
</P>
<P>
The researchers couldn't estimate how many more months or years
the hormonal therapy might add to the life expectancy of a
prostate cancer patient.
</P>
<P>
Yet, more than half the men in the study are still alive eight
years after treatment, Canada's leading newspaper the Globe and
Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
In Canada, prostate cancer is the second-most common cause of
cancer death in men, and its incidence has been increasing by over
5 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 20,000 new cases are diagnosed each year and more than
4,000 men die of it, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
