<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Plans to Restore Civilian Rule in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The military junta will hand
over power to a new civilian government after presidential
election is held in November 2001, according to a statement
broadcast on radio and television today.
</P>
<P>
The statement made by leader of the military government Major
Johnny Paul Koroma said the return to civilian rule will begin
with town, municipal and city council elections held on a
non-party basis in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
It will be followed by district council elections in August
1999 and by provincial assembly elections run on political party
tickets in May 2000. And a national parliamentary election will
follow in February 2001 with presidential election held nine
months later.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made after envoys from ECOWAS broke off
talks with the military junta and recommended tightening economic
sanctions to force it to reverse the May 25 coup in Freetown and
reinstate civilian president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
''We shall not be stampeded into hurrying matter beyond the
appointed time,'' Koroma said in the broadcast. He announced the
immediate setting up of a Constitutional Review Commission but
did not say who its members are.
</P>
<P>
Koroma said he would soon sign a decree to set up a People's
Revolutionary Court, which will be presided over by five
assessors, to try all civil and criminal cases except murder and
treason.
</P>
<P>
He also warned two British based banks -- Barclays and
standard chartered bank, which had been closed since May 26 that
they should ''start operations by Monday, August 4 or their
actions will be regarded as deliberate sabotage" and "we will
withdraw their licenses to operate and force them to liquidate.''
</P>
<P>
Some Sierra Leoneans today called the statement ''a crucial
blow and bombshell''. One irate politician said, ''a four year
time frame is too excessively long. We had hoped the army would
have stayed for at most a year.''
</P>
<P>
In Bo, in the south and the country's second largest city,
many residents reached by phone were ''completely
disillusioned''. In Makeni in the north, where agricultural farms
have been abandoned, residents said they now fear a military
intervention by ECOWAS -- the Economic Community of West African
States -- is imminent.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is leading pressure by the ECOWAS to evict the army
junta from power. For this Koroma called on Nigerian troops to
withdraw from Sierra Leone, saying that Sierra Leone is
reconsidering its membership of a number of unspecified regional
organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
