<HEADLINE> Security Council Decides to Extend Mandate of UNOMIG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of the
United Nations today decided to extend the mandate of the United
Nations Observer Mission in Georgia for a period of six months
until January 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Expressing its deep concern at the continued deadlock in
achieving a comprehensive settlement of the conflict in Abkhaz,
the Security Council reiterated its commitment to the sovereignty
and territorial integrity of Georgia within its internationally
recognized borders and to the necessity of defining the status of
Abkhazia in strict accordance with these principles.
</P>
<P>
Underlining the unacceptability of any action by the Abkhaz
leadership in contravention of these principles, the Security
Council stressed the primary responsibility for reinvigorating the
peace process rests on the parties themselves, and called on them
to achieve substantive progress without further delay towards a
comprehensive political settlement.
</P>
<P>
The council reaffirmed the right of all refugees and displaced
persons affected by the conflict to return to homes in secure
conditions in accordance with international law and condemned the
continued obstruction of the return.
</P>
<P>
It condemned the continued laying of mines, including new types
of mines, in the Gali region and called upon the parties to take
all measures in their power to prevent mine-laying and intensified
activities by armed groups and to cooperate fully with the UNOMIG
and the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) peacekeeping
force in order to honor their commitment to ensure the safety and
freedom of movement of all personnel of the United Nations, the
CIS peacekeeping force and international humanitarian
organizations. 
</P>
