<HEADLINE> Embnargo on S. Leone Tightened as Talks Fails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- West African countries today vowed
to tighten embargo and sanctions on Sierra Leone's military
government as talks for restoring democracy in the troubled
country broke off.
</P>
<P>
In a "final declaration" at the end of the talks in Abidjan,
Cote d'Ivoire, Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi, said the new
position of Sierra Leonean delegation on the issue of reinstating
the civilian government toppled in the May 25 coup was "totally
unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS)
therefore will strengthen economic embargo and sanctions against
the military junta, said Ikimi, leader of the Committee of Four
on Sierra Leone, a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi announced the the collapse of the talks in Abidjan after
military ruler Major Johnny Paul Koroma said the junta "will not
hand over power to a civilian government" until presidential
election is held in November 2001.
</P>
<P>
"It is an affront to ECOWAS. It is an affront to Africa. It is
an affront to the international community," Ikimi said.
</P>
<P>
As the military junta has changed its position, Ikimi said,
the committee considered it "useless to continue discussion" in
Abidjan.
</P>
<P>
The talks, the second round between the two sides to seek ways
to restore the ousted government led by President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah, began on Tuesday and ended abruptly after Koroma's
defiant announcement in the capital Freetown Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The first round negotiation took place two weeks ago and the
committee, made up by foreign ministers of Nigeria, Ghana, Guinea
and Cote d'Ivoire, decided to give the junta a week's time for
another talks.
</P>
<P>
The committee has earlier asked the Koroma regime to hand over
power to Kabbah's government or it will employ embargo or even
force to oust the military junta.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, the blockade by the ECOWAS peace-keeping
force (ECOMOG) has resulted in short supply of foodstuffs and
drugs in the troubled country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
