<HEADLINE> Egypt: Arafat Not Responsible for Bomb Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said here today that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat should not
be blamed for the two bombings in Jerusalem that killed 15 people
and injured more than 170 others Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We should not overstate matters. We have expressed our sorrow
for this incident and to the families of the victims.
Responsibility cannot be placed on President Arafat," Moussa said,
quoted by the Egyptian MENA news agency.
</P>
<P>
Israel blamed the bombings on the Palestinian militants,
accusing Arafat of encouraging such acts, while the U.S. has
demanded the Palestinian leader to take decisive steps to improve
security.
</P>
<P>
Moussa urged all parties to avoid anything which might lead to
an "erosion" of the peace process, stressing that maintaining
peace and security is an important responsibility of all.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has declared a state of emergency and launched an arrest
campaign among Islamic fundamentalists in the
Palestinian-controlled West Bank and Gaza Strip after Wednesday's
bombings, the deadliest since February 1996.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on measures Israel took following the suicide
bombings, Moussa said that the exercise of self-restraint is
important in such circumstances and that no measures should be
taken to make matters more difficult.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with U.S. Ambassador here Edward
Walker, Moussa stressed that it was important that U.S. efforts
should continue to salvage the peace process so that it could not
be destroyed on any pretext.
</P>
<P>
Echoing Israeli President Ezer Weizman's statement that the
latest suicide operation was related to the planned building of an
Israeli settlement at Ras el Amud, Moussa said all measures which
lead to frustration and despair should not continue.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made separate telephone calls to Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy to
express his condolences for the victims of Jerusalem blasts.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of salvaging the peace process so
that all peoples in the area may enjoy security and stability.
</P>
</TEXT>
