<HEADLINE> One in 334 Angolans to be Wounded by Landmine: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- In Angola, one of the countries
which possess the largest number of landmines planted underground
in the world, one out of every 334 people is estimated to be
wounded by the landmine, the Angola News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
South African landmine sweeping expert Van Der Walt told
Angolan military personnel during a landmines clearance course
held in Pretoria, the South African capital, that there are more
than 10 million landmines buried underground all over Angola.
</P>
<P>
The large figure means that every Angolan has more than one
landmines on average, he said, adding that one of every 334
Angolans will be wounded by the landmine.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that nearly 70 people are wounded by the
landmine worldwide every day. More unfortunately, some countries
are continuing to bury landmines, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, since 1996, South Africa has been
helping Angola train professional personnel for landmine
sweeping. So far, scores of Angolan military personnel have been
trained in the field of landmine clerance in South Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
