<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Soldiers Continue to Fight Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of German soldiers today
continued their battle to save homes and crops from flooding in
eastern Germany as a new dike breach on the swollen Oder River
occurred this morning.
</P>
<P>
The new damage was 100 meters south of the gap which opened up
Wednesday in the Oderbruch region on the border with Poland.
</P>
<P>
Military helicopters were dumping thousands of sandbags onto
both sections while 5,000 troops were trying hard to heal the
rupture, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
"The dikes have been badly waterlogged, like jelly," said
Michael Muth, chief of the crisis commission of the eastern German
Brandenburg state.
</P>
<P>
About 2,900 have already been evacuated from the region so far.
Another 10,800 people were also asked to leave today. If the dikes
collapse, floodwaters could submerge an area of over 200 square
kilometers in three to four days, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the army's successful efforts so far, breaches could
occur at any time on the sodden dikes, they added.
</P>
<P>
Weather forecasters meanwhile are predicting more rains for the
coming days. Water levels on the Oder are not expected to go down
considerably until next week.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting in Warsaw today, German and Polish officials
reportedly proposed a joint program with the participation of the
Czech Republic and the European Union to regulate the Oder River
in the future.
</P>
<P>
The plan would involve water retention reservoirs,
environmental protection and dams to protect towns and cities,
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The flood over the past weeks, the worse in central Europe in
200 years, has ravaged 550,000 hectares of land in Poland and one
third of land surface in the Czech Republic, killing 105 people in
the two countries. Germany has seen three border villages flooded,
but no casualties have been reported so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
