<HEADLINE> First Eastern African Stamp Show Opens in Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The first-ever eastern African
stamp exhibition, with thousands of delicate stamps on display
and sale, attracted hundreds of enthusiastic visitors here on its
first day today.
</P>
<P>
The three-day exhibition, sponsored by the postal authorities
of Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda and several regional stamp clubs,
was aimed at promoting philately and close cooperation between
philatelists in the region, said the organizers.
</P>
<P>
The organizers said they also hoped the show, with key topics
on wildlife, plants, flowers, sports and local arts, can
encourage young people to use their spare time for this
interesting and educative hobby.
</P>
<P>
Although the organizers lamented that stamp collection are
old-fashioned among and neglected by the young generation in the
region, cheerful teenagers poured into the crowded fair and
showed strong interest in stamps riotous with color.
</P>
<P>
Many visitors registered and paid fees for taking part in
stamp clubs on the scene.
</P>
<P>
Four series of stamps designed to commemorate late Chinese
leader Deng Xiaoping, two issued by Tanzania and the others by
Uganda, caused special attention and sold well.
</P>
<P>
The first east Africa stamps, square-shaped in red brown, were
issued in considerable quantity by Britain in 1890. Each of them,
if unused, now worths 500 pounds (some 816 U.S. Dollars), an aged
veteran philatelist told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The three eastern African countries, all once British
colonies, only issued stamps respectively by their own after they
declared independence in 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Currently Kenya issues five to eight series of stamps annually
while Tanzania four to eight and Uganda eight to 12, said the
organizers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
