<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Economic Growth Slows Down in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. economic growth slowed
down sharply in the second quarter of this year, the U.S. Commerce
Department said today.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) expanded at a moderate 2.2
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate in the second quarter,
declined from a robust 4.9 percent rate in the first quarter and a
4.3 percent rate during the final three months of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. Labor Department said the number of
American workers filing first-time claims for unemployment
benefits fell by 22,000 last week to a seasonally adjusted
277,000, the lowest level in more than 23 years.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending -- accounting for about two-thirds of the
economy's output -- was the big factor. Their spending grew at a
lackluster 0.8 percent rate in the second quarter after surging at
a 5.3 percent rate in the first.
</P>
<P>
A key inflation gauge tied to the GDP rose at a scant 1.4
percent annual rate, down from 2.4 percent in the first quarter
and the lowest in 34 years.
</P>
<P>
Other factors detracting from growth in the second quarter
included a slowing in the accumulation of goods in inventories and
a deterioration in the trade balance. The fastest import growth in
13 years, 21.8 percent at an annual rate, swamped the 14.4 percent
rate of increase in exports.
</P>
<P>
Business investment, however, increased as did home building
and government spending. Business investment in new plants and
equipment grew at a 15.1 percent rate, more than triple the 4.1
percent pace of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
House and apartment construction grew at a 5.6 percent rate, up
from 3.3 percent in the previous quarter. Government spending
which includes that at local, state and federal levels, advanced
at a 3.8 percent pace, in contrast with a slight decline in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The country's economic output in the second quarter stands at
an inflation-adjusted annual rate of 7.14 trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department today also issued revised GDP figures
back to 1993. It showed the economy grew a bit faster last year
than the previous estimate, 2.8 percent compared with 2.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
