<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Turkish Cypriot Leaders Agree on Missing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash agreed today to
solve the long-standing issue of missing persons during Turkey's
invasion of the island in 1974.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed to provide each other "immediately and
simultaneously" with all information at their disposal regarding
the location of graves, U.N. Resident Representative Gustave
Feissel told reporters after a meeting between Clerides and
Denktash this evening at his residence in the U.N.-controlled
Nicosia airport area.
</P>
<P>
This is the second meeting between Clerides and Denktash
within a week to discuss the humanitarian issues which
constitute an important aspect of the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,619 Greek Cypriots and Greeks were listed as
missing after 30,000 Turkish military personnel landed and took
over one third of the northern eastern Mediterranean island in
1974 following a pro-Athens coup by some Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Feissel said both leaders also agreed to appoint persons who
will exchange this information and prepare the necessary
arrangement leading to the return of the remains of the missing
persons by this September.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official also announced that President Clerides and
Denktash agreed that the remains of persons killed in action
will also be returned to their families.
</P>
<P>
Feissel said the two leaders consider the issue of the
missing as purely humanitarian and agreed not to exploit it
politically.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy noted that a number of other humanitarian
issues were also discussed, and something will be announced in a
few days.
</P>
<P>
He added that Clerides and Denktash found "useful" their
meetings in Nicosia this week and indicated their readiness for
further meetings of this kind to deal with humanitarian matters
in the future.
</P>
<P>
The two meetings took place after the first round of the
direct negotiations between the two leaders at Troutbeck, near
New York from July 9 to 12.
</P>
<P>
The second round of U.N.-led direct talks between the two
communities' leaders are scheduled on August 11-16 in
Switzerland to continue searching solution to the Cyprus problem
which has remained unsolved since 1974.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
