<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq in Dreadful Shortage of Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A hospital in the Karbalaa
governorate of Iraq, 90 kilometers south of capital Baghdad, has
seen 39 deformed newly-born babies in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq News Agency today quoted the hospital director as
saying that this is due to the dreadful shortage of vaccines and
other medicine, a damaging result of the seven-year-old
U.N. sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.4 million people, including 750,000 children below the
age of five, have perished because of the scarcity of food and
medicine since the U.N. embargo took effect in 1990 for its
invasion of Kuwait which sparked the Gulf War, according to
statistics released by the Iraqi Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The situation continues devastating. Under its oil-for-food
deal with the U.N. last December, Iraq was allowed to purchase 7
million U.S. dollars worth of medicine and medical instruments from
foreign pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
This amount, however, is far from adequate compared with its
annual import of some 2 billion dollars worth of medical supplies
in the years before the U.N. sanctions were imposed.
</P>
<P>
Shelves have long been empty in state-run drug stores and
hospitals. Even the most commonly used medicine, such as
penicillin and other anti-biotics, are rare in black markets,
</P>
<P>
A tube of tetracycline, for example, is sold in the black
market at a skyrocketing price of 800 Iraqi dinars (about 0.6
dollars) when monthly salary for an average government employee
range between 4,000 and 5,000 dinars (three to four dollars).
</P>
<P>
What makes things worse is that state-run hospitals are not
able to keep their qualified doctors from leaving, battered by low
salaries. People have to go to private clinics for basic medical
help.
</P>
<P>
But most of them are daunted away by the appalling price tags
in the private clinics as visit fee normally stands as high as
12,000 dinars (about nine dollars), almost equaling three months'
salary and barely affordable for an ordinary income-earner.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) warned in February that
Iraq's medical system is going to collapse because of the shortage
of medicine and medical facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970801.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Changes Lending Rates on Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) today announced changes in its lending rates on the
convertible-currency portion of loans from the ordinary capital
for the second semester of 1997.
</P>
<P>
For outstanding balances of currency-pool rate loans approved
after January 1, 1990, the lending rate will be 6.59 percent in
the second half of 1997 as compared with 6.68 percent in the first
semester.
</P>
<P>
For disbursements on loans approved between January 1, 1983,
and December 31, 1989, the lending rate is 6.97 percent, as
against 6.73 percent in first semester of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The lending rate applicable to outstanding balance of variable
rate loans in U.S. dollars from the single currency facility (SCF)
is 6.97 percent. For loans denominated in German marks the rate is
6.66 percent, for Japanese yen, 3.37 percent and for Swiss francs,
4.58 percent, which are all lowered than the previous ones.
</P>
<P>
The previous SCF lending rates in effect, during the first
semester of 1997, were U.S. dollars 6.90 percent, German marks
6.95 percent, Japanese yen 3.69 percent and Swiss francs 4.98
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
