<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Peacekeepers Still in Abkhazia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The mandate of the Russian
peacekeepers in Abkhazia expires on Thursday, but their activities
in the conflict zone will not be stopped, the Itar-Tass news
agency quoted a senior Russian military official as reporting on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant-General Alexander Arinakhin, who is an aide to the
head of Russia's General Headquarters for peacekeeping operations,
said that the decision to terminate the peacekeepers activity can
only be taken by a CIS (Commonwealth of Independent States) summit
which had issued the mandate.
</P>
<P>
He said that such a decision on behalf of CIS leaders can also
be made by the present chairman of the CIS Council -- Russian
president Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Arinakhin continued, the peacekeepers' activities can
be terminated upon an official demand by one of the conflicting
sides. But, neither Georgia, nor Abkhazia has made such statements
yet, he added.
</P>
<P>
Another report from Tbilisi, Georgia's capital, said that
Georgia will not insist in holding the peacekeeping forces in the
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict zone.
</P>
<P>
Levan Aleksidze, Georgian presidential adviser and a major
legal expert in the Georgian delegation at the talks on settlement
in Abkhazia, said on Thursday "We will wait" for decisions the
CIS summit in the fall will make.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at the same day Georgian Defense Minister Vardiko
Nadibaidze flew Moscow on a special commission from Georgian
President Eduard Shevardnadze to discuss problems pertaining to
the expiration of the Russian peacekeepers' mandate in Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
The Russian peacekeepers were brought into the conflict zone on
June 23, 1994, in line with the ceasefire and disengagement
agreement dated May 14, 1994.
</P>
<P>
A CIS summit in the spring of 1997 extended their mandate until
July 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Russia's contingent of peacekeepers in Abkhazia currently
numbers 1,600. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
