<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Advisory Team Gathers to Assess Mideast Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton's Middle
East advisory team on Thursday gathered at the White House to
discuss the situations after suicide bombings at a Jerusalem
market, which killed 15 people and injured more than 150, the
White House said.
</P>
<P>
The team will discuss developments and "next steps" in the
stalemated peace process, White House press secretary Mike McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
"I doubt very much they will present recommendations to the
president at this point. It's more of an assessment meeting,"
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton is not expected to attend the meeting, but
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who cut short an Asian
trip, Middle East mediator Dennis Ross and national Security
Adviser Sandy Berger were to take part in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The suicide bombings at the Jerusalem market, which killed 15
people and injured more than 150, was the deadliest attack since
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu won election in 1996.
The Islamic militant movement Hamas claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Clinton on Wednesday condemned the bombings as a barbarous act,
and called on Palestinian President Yasser Arafat to take concrete
steps to strengthen security in the region.
</P>
<P>
Albright has said on her way back to Washington that Arafat
had assured her to commit himself to restoring security in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
