<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Approves Balanced Budget Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Senate today approved a
legislation to balance the budget and shrink the size of the
federal government after the House of Representatives did so on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bill, passed with a bipartisan vote of 85-15, will be sent
to President Bill Clinton for signature.
</P>
<P>
The bill called for about 130 billion U.S. dollars in spending
restraint needed to balance the budget. Meanwhile, the measure
remodels Medicare and creates a new 24 billion U.S. dollars
program of health care for uninsured children insisted on by the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Clinton called the budget bill "the
achievement of a generation and a triumph for every American,"
adding that it marks an end to decades of deficits.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the bill is "the achievement of generation and
a triumph for every American," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"This good for America," said Senate Republican Leader Trent
Lott. "It's a major step forward. Maybe not a leap, but a major
step."
</P>
<P>
The balanced budget bill, a measure designed to rid the nation
of deficits for the first time since 1969, had held center stage
in both the Senate and the House.
</P>
<P>
With the budget bill cleared for Clinton's approval, lawmakers
turned their attention to the 151.6 billion U.S. dollars five-year
tax cut legislation.
</P>
<P>
The House is expected to pass it later in the day while the
Senate is to approve it on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
