<HEADLINE> Cohen Faults U.S. General over Saudi Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said today that the commander of a U.S. air base in Saudi
Arabia failed to adequately protect against a terrorist strike
that killed 19 U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting President Bill Clinton, Cohen said he
was blocking the promotion of Brig. Gen. Terryl Schwalier, whose
unit lost 19 airmen to a huge truck bomb explosion that tore
through the Dhahran barracks known as Khobar Towers on June 15,
1996.
</P>
<P>
"The president accepted my recommendation that Brig. General
Schwalier's name be withdrawn from the promotion list, " Cohen
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Cohen faulted Schwalier for failing to adequately assess the
threat to the perimeter of the housing complex and prepare for a
possible bombing.
</P>
<P>
Cohen's decision goes against two internal Air Force reports,
which contended Schwalier did everything he could have done for
the safety of the men and women at the complex in Dhahran.
</P>
</TEXT>
