<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Attempt Foiled in N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The British bomb disposal officers
carried out a controlled explosion today in a car at a hotel in
Northern Ireland, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
Twelve days ago, the Irish Republican Army declared ceasefire
in Northern Ireland in order to allow its political wing Sinn Fein
to take part in the substantive peace talks in September.
</P>
<P>
The device, reportedly containing up to 450 kilograms of
home-made explosive, was assumed to have been planted Thursday
night near the hotel in County Fermanagh, about 160 kilometers
west of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Police said they were alerted to the device by two telephone
calls but without giving further details.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam today condemned the car
bomb attempt and asked for a full investigation.
</P>
<P>
No groups have claimed responsibility so far but security
forces suspect the Continuity Army Council (CAC) to be linked.
</P>
<P>
CAC is opposed to negotiations with Britain and says that an
end to rule of Northern Ireland by London will only come about by
force.
</P>
<P>
IRA, the key outlawed guerrilla organization which has been
fighting against the British rule of Northern Ireland since 1969
called for a ceasefire on July 20, bringing hopes to boost the
stalled Northern Ireland peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
