<DOCNO> XIE19970801.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli President Calls for Return to Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
today called for a return to the Israeli-Arab peace talks despite
Wednesday's suicide bombings in Jerusalem, warning that all sides
will lose if the peace process collapses.
</P>
<P>
Weizman made this appeal in Abu Ghosh near Jerusalem during a
condolence visit to the family of an Arab victim of the double
bombings, which took 15 lives and wounded over 170 in central
Mahane Yehuda vegetable and fruit market.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Israeli militant Palestinian organization Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas) has claimed responsibility, though
Israeli security forces have not proved the authenticity of the
claim.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the stupidity of the bombings surpassed any other
previous terror attacks in Israel, Weizman said the tragedy
indicated the need for a common future for both Israelis and Arabs.
</P>
<P>
The president also expressed the hope that both sides would
understand bombs and terror would not achieve anything, and urged
Israelis and Arabs to return to the negotiating table. "Everyone
would lose if the peace process collapses," Weizman said.
</P>
<P>
Weizman's call appeared to be the most sober and rational voice
ever heard from Israeli leaders since the tragic bombings that
incurred tough reactions from Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
Blaming the bombings on the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA), Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process could not continue until the
Palestinian side launches an all-out war against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He threatened to dispatch Israeli troops to re-enter
Palestinian self-rule areas to track down Arab extremists, a move
that was criticized by the PNA as a "declaration of war."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leaders have warned about the danger of killing the
peace process and of pushing the region back to war in the
aftermath of the bomb attack.
</P>
<P>
The Wednesday bombings erased the newly emerging optimism over
breaking the prolonged deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process caused by Israel's building of controversial Har Homa
settlement in East Jerusalem in March. Only two days before, the
two sides agreed to restart political negotiations some time in
the week.
</P>
<P>
The terror attack also canceled a planned visit to the region
by the United States Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross, who was
about to kick off, starting Thursday, a new round of mediation
aimed at achieving quick progress in the Israeli-Palestinian
peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
