<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More UK Women Return to Work soon after Having Baby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- More and more working women in
Britain return to their jobs soon after having a baby due to
financial and career pressures, according to a report published
today.
</P>
<P>
The report, Maternity Rights and Benefits, by the Policy
Studies Institute, said that two out of three women now go back to
work shortly after giving birth, compared with less than half in
1988, an increase of 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report, funded by the government and based on
interviews with managers in 1,485 workplaces and a postal survey
of 2,051 mothers, showed that women are taking less time off work
before having their babies.
</P>
<P>
More than a third of women continued to work during the six
weeks before childbirth last year, compared with only 15 percent
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Women are also more likely to return sooner after the birth,
with 81 percent going back within 28 weeks in 1996, compared with
75 percent in 1988.
</P>
<P>
On average, women took 27 weeks' maternity leave in 1996, but
14 percent who were entitled to the statutory minimum of 14 weeks
took less than that amount.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the changes in women's work patterns may
be due in some cases to financial pressures, but others may be
trying to minimize any disruption to their careers.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the study, Harriet Harman, the social security
secretary, said that the report provided vital new information and
one of the government's key aims was to promote measures that
would help people to balance the demands of work and family life.
</P>
<P>
"We will do all that we can to encourage employers to make
improvements in the workplace generally, in particular in the
provision of flexible and family-friendly working arrangements,"
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
