<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Unemployment Declines to 4.8 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. unemployment rate
dropped to a near 24-year low of 4.8 percent in July after moving
up in June, but wage growth stalled, the Labor Department said
today.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted unemployment rate marks a decline from
5 percent in June and matches the May rate, the lowest rate since
November 1973.
</P>
<P>
However, the strong job market has not produced bigger
paychecks. Seasonally adjusted average hourly earnings of nonfarm
production and nonsupervisory workers were unchanged at 12.23
dollars an hour.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that the unemployment rate has fallen from 5.4
percent a year earlier, hourly wage growth has actually slowed.
It's averaged 2.9 cents a month so far this year, compared with
3.8 cents in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a separate report today from the Commerce Department
said that Americans' income grew 0.6 percent in June, the largest
in three months, while their spending increased by 0.3 percent for
the second straight month.
</P>
<P>
In July, according to Bureau of Labor Statistics Commissioner
Katharine G. Abraham, employment growth was concentrated in
services, retail trade and local government.
</P>
<P>
Health services rose by 31,000 jobs and growth was quite strong
in engineering and management services and computer services, she
said. Retailers added 65,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Local education accounted for almost the entire increase of
56,000 government jobs. Manufacturing jobs fell by 5,000 and
construction rose 3,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
