<HEADLINE> Russian President Names New Deputy PM for Ethnic Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 1 (Xinhua) - Russian President Boris Yeltsin has
named Ramazan Abdulatipov, deputy to the Russian State Duma, as
new deputy prime minister in charge of ethnic relations,
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The appointment was announced today by the president on
holiday at the Volga river resort of Volzhsky Utyos in central
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Ramazan Abdulatipov, a former deputy speaker of the upper house
of parliament, was elected to a deputy to the State Duma, the
lower house, in 1996. He will be the seventh deputy premier in the
government.
</P>
<P>
Abdulatipov comes from the multi-ethnic North Caucasus republic
of Dagestan, which borders the Caspian Sea and the republic
of Chechnya, and is a member of the tiny Avar ethnic minority.
</P>
<P>
His appointment comes amid renewed tension between two other
North Caucasus Russian republics -- Ingushetia and North Ossetia.
</P>
<P>
In a 1992 war, many ethnic Ingush people living in North
Ossetia were driven out of the republic. In recent weeks, conflict
in the area has escalated as these Ingush refugees trying to
return came under a new wave of violent attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
