<HEADLINE> Six South Korean Companies Allowed to Cooperate With DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea today allowed five
firms to invest in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK) and another one to participate in its light water reactors
(LWR) construction program.
</P>
<P>
With the approval, the Samsung Electronics Co., South Korea's
largest electronics company, will invest some 5 million
U.S. dollars to produce communication-related products in DPRK's
Rajin-Sonbong Free Trade Zone in partnership with DPRK's Korea
Telecom Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Kolon Co., a leading manufacturer of textile products, plans to
invest some 4 million dollars in a textile processing plant with
DPRK's Unha General Trading Corp.
</P>
<P>
Another three companies -- Shinwon Co., Parason Fishery and
Kumo Food Co., plan to cooperate with their counterparts in the
DPRK in clothing production and food processing.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Electricity Power Corporation will help DPRK's
Post and Telecommunication Ministry improve its telecommunication
facilities needed in the construction of the LWR.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached between the DPRK and the United
States in 1994, Pyongyang agreed to freeze its nuclear program
suspected of producing nuclear weapons in exchange for the two
LWRs. 
</P>
