<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5,000-Year History of Chinese Handwriting: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese handwriting by using hard
utensils has a history of more than 5,000 years, according to a
Chinese expert Li Zhengyu.
</P>
<P>
Li, an expert on Dunhuang Research in northwest China's Gansu
Province, said that ancient Chinese used wood, bamboo, bone, gold
and stone as pens with which to write and draw, much earlier than
the use of calligraphic writing brushes.
</P>
<P>
The handwriting was very popular before the Qin Dynasty
(221-206 B.C.), and people not only used hard materials for
drawing pictures, but also use them as writing utensils, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The carving patterns on 7,000-year old pottery items unearthed
in the Dadiwan Cultural Ruins are regarded as the original form of
Chinese characters, and the 4,000-year old carving utensils in the
Yin Dynasty were regarded the earliest pens, he said.
</P>
<P>
A number of handwriting forms appeared in the Zhou Dynasty, and
many kinds of hard writing utensils had been created from the West
Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-A.D.24) to the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970801.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Currency Policy Committee Formed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The State Council has appointed
members of the newly-formed Currency Policy Committee of the
People's Bank of China (PBOC).
</P>
<P>
PBOC Governor Dai Xianglong has been appointed chairman of the
committee; PBOC Vice-Governor Chen Yuan has been named
vice-chairman.
</P>
<P>
The other members of the committee are: PBOC Vice-Governor
Shang Fulin; Vice-Minister of the State Planning Commission Wang
Chunzheng; Vice-Minister of the State Economic and Trade
Commission Chen Qingtai; Vice-Minister of Finance Xie Xuren,
Director of the State Foreign Exchange Administration Zhou
Xiaochuan; Vice-Chairman of the State Securities Regulatory
Commission Chen Yaoxian; President of the Industrial and
Commercial Bank of China Liu Tinghuan; President of the
Agricultural Bank of China Shi Jiliang; and the former president
of China's People's University Huang Da.
</P>
<P>
Following its first meeting presided over by Dai Xianglong
Thursday, the committee members agreed that the country should
continue its moderately-tight monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The group also put forward a number of proposals on currency
policies, financial supervision, financial services and other
related issues.
</P>
<P>
The committee decided to hold a regular meeting in the first
month of every quarter.
</P>
<P>
Local experts believe that the establishment of the committee
will be beneficial to the drafting of state currency policies,
improving the level of decision-making on the macro-financial
level, and bolstering the sustained, rapid and healthy development
of the national economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
