<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Birth Rate Picks Up in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The fertility decline which has
afflicted the European Union (EU) countries for years has come to
an end as women there averaged 1.44 babies in 1996, according to a
statement of Eurostat, EU's statistics arm, today.
</P>
<P>
Ireland registered the highest rate of 1.91 babies per woman
whereas Spain's 1.15 was the lowest. A total of just over four
million babies were born in EU countries last year.
</P>
<P>
The year 1995 registed a post-war record low of 1.43 babies per
woman after years' of successive decline,
</P>
<P>
The EU population rose by an estimated 1,037,600 to 373,691,200
last year and the growth rate was nearly 0.3 percent, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Attributing the fertility decline to postponed motherhood, the
statement said last year's birth rate recovery was due to
immigration.
</P>
<P>
It said immigrants contributed a post-war high of nearly 80
percent of the EU population growth in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Births by immigrants last year, though falling from those of
1995, still accounted for three-quarters of the EU population
increase, it added.
</P>
<P>
World population grew by some 81 million last year, and the EU
contributed 1.3 percent to the growth, the statement pointed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
