<HEADLINE> German Crude Oil Imports Down in First Half of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Germany's crude oil imports fell by
some 2.5 percent in the first half of this year from the same
period of 1996, the Federal Office for Economy based in
Eschborn said today.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the country imported some 48.3 million tons
of crude, with the bill up 12 percent or 12.1 billion marks (6.5
billion U.S. dollars) as the price increased by 14.8 percent to an
averaged 250.12 marks (about 125.1 dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
Russia remained the largest oil supplier, with 12.4
million tons, which was followed by Norway with 10.5 million
tons and Britain with 7.2 million tons.
</P>
<P>
British and Norwegian North Sea oil sources accounted for some
36.8 percent of the imports, while the Organization for Petroleum
Exporting Countries accounted for 29.8 percent, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
