<HEADLINE> India Wants Friendship with All Neighbors: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral said today that India does not have any hegemonic
designs on its neighbors and "Gujral Doctrine" is basically
extending a firm hand of friendship to all neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating an Afro-Asian students' meeting at Symbiosis
International Cultural and Educational Center in Pune city, about
1,500 km southwest of New Delhi, the prime minister said, "My
concept of neighborhood does not confine itself to South Asia. It
includes the countries in the Indian Ocean rim, Southeast Asia,
Central Asia, Russia and China."
</P>
<P>
"After a great period of turmoil and agony we have turned
corners in so far as South Asia is concerned. The summit meeting
of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) in
Male, capital of the Maldives, (in May this year) was a turning
point as there was a realization and appreciation that we must
build a region and cannot go up singly," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the Male SAARC summit meeting, Indian and Pakistani Prime
Ministers Gujral and Nawaz Sharif in their bilateral talks agreed
to solve their disputes through peaceful talks and decided to set
up several working groups to discuss their differences. Inspired
by their sincerity in improving their bilateral relations,
Bangladesh, Bhutan, the Maldives, Nepal and Sri Lanka expressed
their desire to further enhance cooperation among the member
nations.
</P>
<P>
As India gets into the next half century it must give
friendship and cooperation in larger degree, Gujral said.
</P>
</TEXT>
