<HEADLINE> EU to Offer Germany Flood Relief Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Union will provide
the German state of Brandenburg with a flood relief fund of 1.5
million ECU's (1.62 million U.S. dollars), European Report said
today.
</P>
<P>
The Report quoted Monika Wulf-Mathies, European commissioner in
charge of regional policy, as saying that the money will be used
to help the battered region cope with the worst flooding for more
than 200 years.
</P>
<P>
The fund, however, would be formally approved in September by
the European Parliament when it reconvenes after the summer break,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Germany is reportedly keen to funnel the emergency fund to
farmers in the flood-threatened Oderbruch region, where some 5,000
hectares of farmland is currently under flood water.
</P>
<P>
German troops and emergency services are working hard to
prevent the low-lying Oderbruch basin, with 76,000 hectares of
farmland at risk, from joining the disaster area.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the European Union has granted an emergency money of 2
million ECU's (2.16 million dollars) to Poland and the Czech
Republic which have also been seriously affected by the flooding
Oder river. 
</P>
