<DOCNO> XIE19970801.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Free Trade Area to be Set up in East and Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for East and
Southern Africa (COMESA) is expected to set up a free trade area
in the year 2000 in a bid to quicken the pace of regional
economic integration, a senior COMESA official said today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here this morning after a one-day
seminar attended by business community in Kenya, acting COMESA
Secretary General Erastus Mwencha said the idea conformed to the
strategy of "promoting regional economic integration through
trade development".
</P>
<P>
He noted that the launching of the free trade area would offer
"exciting challenges and opportunities" to entrepreneurs in the
region for trade and cross-border investment.
</P>
<P>
The planned COMESA single market would have a combined Gross
Domestic Product (GDP) of 120 billion U.S. Dollars and a total
population of 320 million.
</P>
<P>
According to him, five member states, namely Comoros, Eritrea,
Sudan, Uganda and Zimbabwe, have reduced their tariff rates by 80
percent while the tariff rates in Kenya, Malawi and Mauritius
have declined by 70 percent and would drop by 80 percent in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
Burundi, Rwanda and Zambia have reduced their tariff rates by
60 percent and all the three countries are in the process of
cutting their tariffs pursuant to the COMESA timetable.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho, Namibia and Swaziland have not reduced tariffs
because they are still enjoying derogation and are expected to
implement the COMESA tariffs after the expiry of the derogation.
</P>
<P>
Following the tariff reduction coupled with other measures,
the intra-COMESA trade has grown at an average annual rate of 14
percent, compared with 7 percent growth among COMESA and
non-COMESA countries.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics showed that the intra-COMESA trade
increased from 838 million Dollars in 1984 to 1.7 billion Dollars
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Studies undertaken by the COMESA Secretariat revealed that
there was 3 billion Dollars of intra-COMESA trade which can be
immediately materialized.
</P>
<P>
In order to promote intra-COMESA trade, Mwencha pointed out,
COMESA will introduce a Customs Union and harmonize documentation
and institutional requirements in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
COMESA has implemented programs on fiscal and monetary
harmonization with the last phase introducing a single currency
in the year 2025, he added.
</P>
<P>
The programs being implemented by the COMESA Secretariat in
productive sectors of agriculture and industry are supportive of
the strategy of COMESA market integration, the COMESA official
stated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
