<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai-Xinjiang Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial center, and the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, the
nation's westernmost region, recently consummated a science
and technology (S&AMP;T) cooperation agreement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for the Shanghai Academy of Sciences (SAS) to
supply the Xinjiang Dushanzi Petrochemical Plant with automatic
ignition and gas recovery equipment, as well as coal additives.
</P>
<P>
Technology transfers and new equipment will enable the plant to
sharply reduce emissions of suspended particles, and are expected
to increase annual profits by more than 10 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
SAS, one of the nation's most prestigious academies, will also
supply the plant with stereo storage systems, steam recovery
equipment and technological consulting. In addition, the agreement
calls for the academy to sponsor S&AMP;T research programs for the
plant.
</P>
<P>
Delegations of SAS experts will visit Xinjiang twice each year
to explore new opportunities for cooperation and introduce new
high technology from Shanghai to local enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to Dushanzi plant director Chen Zongyu, "Cooperation
with highly developed coastal and inland areas will enable
Xinjiang to overcome a lack of professional technicians,
contribute greatly to economic growth in ethnic minority areas,
and help to strengthen national unity."
</P>
<P>
The plant, which employees 14,000 people, has an annual
ethylene production capacity of 140,000 tons, and an annual
refined oil processing capacity of six million tons. Dushanzi
recorded total sales of 4.9 billion yuan in sales last year,
a major contributor to local revenues.
</P>
<P>
The central government has called for more of the nation's
developed eastern areas to seek common prosperity by assisting
underdeveloped regions in the west. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
