<HEADLINE> Hopes Fade on Australia's Ski Lodge Survival: Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Relatives of the 16 people
believed trapped in Thredbo's landslide disaster were today told
by police to expect the worst as rescue efforts at the ski resort
ground to a near-halt.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 400 emergency workers stood by helplessly as a
massive boulder teetered dangerously above the rubble of the two
smashed ski lodges, the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers tonight uncovered two more bodies from the ruins
of the ski lodge disaster, police said.
</P>
<P>
The discovery brings to four the total of confirmed deaths with
16 people believed inside the two collapsed lodges still
unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
Late today the boulder was secured and workers tonight were
cutting up a huge concrete slab with diamond-tipped chainsaws to
expose the next layer of rubble.
</P>
<P>
Regional Police Commander Charlie Sanderson said the chance of
finding survivors now was small with mud and debris up to 10
meters deep. Temperature in the ski resort, which is about 150 km
southeast of the nation's capital Canberra, plunged well below the
freezing point for the third successive night.
</P>
<P>
The first body was removed from the wreckage by firemen late
last night, almost 24 hours after the landslide that swept one ski
lodge on top of another, and a second body was detected this
morning.
</P>
<P>
But tonight the second body remained well out of reach, about
10-15 meters below the first slab.
</P>
<P>
Among those the local residents fear are missing, believed
trapped in the rubble, are Mim Sodergren and Mike Sodergren, ski
instructors from the United States, and New Zealand-born ski
instructor Mary Phillips. The other unidentified missing people
are believed to be Australians working for the ski resort.
</P>
<P>
Police say it could take several days for everyone to be
removed.
</P>
<P>
The disaster, which occurred at midnight Wednesday, shocked the
whole nation as one of the worst fatal natural calamities in
Australia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
