<HEADLINE> Zambia's Chibuluma Copper Mines Sold to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Chibuluma mines in Zambia's
copperbelt have been sold to Metorex Consortium which is
comprised of two South African mining firms and one Canadian
company as part of the ongoing privatization of the country's
copper mines.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted Luke Mwananshiku, chairman of the
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), as announcing here on
Wednesday that "the privatization of Chibuluma mine assets
guarantees the development of Chibuluma south."
</P>
<P>
"It is also in line with one of government's objectives of
diversifying the ownership of the mining industry on the
copperbelt and ensures that Kalulushi town will not be a ghost
town after cessation of mining at Chibuluma mines," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chibuluma mine assets include Chibuluma south and west ore
bodies, the mining and ancillary equipment necessary for the
operation of the west mine, and the social assets.
</P>
<P>
The social assets constitute the operation of Kalulushi
hospital, the trust school, the general upkeep of the town and
mine facilities including roads, water, sewerage and parks.
</P>
<P>
The buyers have undertaken to develop Chibuluma south for over
three to four years to cover production shortfalls arising from
the gradual cessation of operations at the mines within five
years.
</P>
<P>
So far the Luanshya, Baluba and Kansanshi copper mines and a
power division have been sold under the ZCCM privatization
program to revive the country's ailing copper-mining industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
