<HEADLINE> Australia's Heroin Trials to Face Int'l Scrutiny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Australia will have to convince
the world community of the benefits of its controversial heroin
trials to ensure it does not break the country's international
drug enforcement commitments, experts said today.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting in Australia's northeast coastal city of Cairns
Thursday evening, health ministers from states and territories of
the country approved the first stage of a heroine trial in
Canberra. The planned trial will see 40 drug addicts given
controlled doses of heroin under medical supervision.
</P>
<P>
The state of Victoria announced today trials on supplying
heroin addicts with alternative drugs could start within three
months in the state. The trials, which are expected to take three
years before producing reliable results, will involve a total of
400 drug addicts at a cost of about 1.5 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But Australia will need to convince the International Drug
Commission to make sure the trial does not upset international
agreements designed to crack down on the drugs trade.
</P>
<P>
Professor David Pennington, an advocate for heroin trial, said
Australia would need to convince the international community that
the trials would be in the interest of scientific and medical
research.
</P>
<P>
Doctors today welcomed the trial's approval, saying current
methods to control drugs have not worked.
</P>
<P>
"Increasing numbers are dying as the result of heroin overdose.
Current laws have simply not worked," said Dr. Peter Joseph,
president of the Royal Australian College of General
Practitioners.
</P>
<P>
Victorian Premier Jeff Kennett said heroin and heroin
substitution trials might be the solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
However, the planned trials did not win universal support.
</P>
<P>
The New South Wales state opposition and church groups said it
sent the wrong message to the community on drugs. The trial
decision was opposed Thursday by the states of Queensland and
Western Australia and the Northern Territory.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
