<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- A man who tried since April to
blackmail Germany's leading chain store company Tengelmann group
by threatening poisoning supermarket food has been arrested, said
reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old unemployed was arrested early Thursday, said
police authorities in Munich, and has admitted trying to blackmail
the Tengelmann group of five million marks (about 2.8 million
U.S. dollars) in credit cards.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested while using one of the cards to collect cash from
dispensing machines.
</P>
<P>
Tengelmann has more than 7,000 shops around the world, including
supermarkets, drug stores and general stores. It is Germany's fifth
largest food retailer.  
