<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Jobs Lost in S.Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 1 (Xinhua) -- A further 42,000 jobs were
lost in South Africa's non-agricultural sector during the
first quarter of this year, figures released Thursday by the
government said.
</P>
<P>
The government's Growth, Employment and Redistribution
Strategy (GEAR) had projected the creation of 126,000 jobs last
year and 252,000 this year, none of which have materialised.
</P>
<P>
The latest figure comes when an increasing number of
economists are predicting that the economy will slip into
recession this year and register two consecutive quarters of
negative growth of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
South Africa's GDP dropped 0.8 percent during the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Local daily The Star today quoted government officials as
saying that the time had come for its GEAR strategy to be
supplemented with a comprehensive development plan to boost jobs.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1996 figures released by the government,
South Africa's unemployment rate is about 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
If the unemployment rate continue to accelerate, said the
officials, nearly 170,000 workers could be laid off this year
compared with 71,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that jobs were lost in most economic sectors,
including government organizations which, until the end of
1996, had been creating employment.
</P>
<P>
The hardest hit was the manufacturing sector, which recorded
a 14,000 job-loss during the first quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
