<HEADLINE> Israel Yet to Identify Suicide Bombers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel is still unable to tell
the identification of the two suicide bombers of Wednesday's
bombing attack in Jerusalem after DNA tests showed there was no
relationship between the bombers and the families of two missing
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The twin bombings at a market in Jewish west Jerusalem killed
killed 13 Israelis and wounded 168 others.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the state-run Israel Radio today,
investogators into the incident have begun to look for other
directions after DNA test showed that there was no relationship
between the bombers and the families of the two missing Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas) activists from Dahariya, a village
south of the West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
The Institute for Forensic Medicine at Abu Kabir conducted the
test on the families of two missing Hamas activists and the bodies
of the two bombers, and conveyed the results to the security
forces.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops detained the families shortly after the suicide
bombing attack on Wednesday. The two young men, who were known as
Hamas activists, disappeared more than a year ago. The families
were taken to the morgue to see the bodies of the bombers, but
said they could not identify them.
</P>
<P>
The security forces, who were misled by their overconfidence
in believing that the two bombers were the two missing Dahariya
men, now have to consider other possibilities.
</P>
<P>
Although they do not rule out the possibility that the two
attackers came from abroad, they still believe the bombers were
Hamas activists from the Palestinian territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
