<HEADLINE> Governor: Macao Security Neither Too Good Nor Too Bad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Macao Governor General Vasco Rocha
Vieira said that the security situation in Macao is "not too good,
 but not too bad," Macao Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the governor made the remarks several
hours after a bomb exploded around 7:40 p.m. (local time) on
Thursday outside the headquarters of Macao security forces,
damaging two cars slightly but causing no injuries.
</P>
<P>
The attack by a bottle filled with gunpowder was described by a
 police spokesman last night as an "act of provocation by the
triads."
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday morning, a similar incendiary gadget,
which was described as a "firecracker," was thrown into the garden
 of the Government Palace but caused no damage. The palace
includes the governor's office and the Macao Legislative Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The latest wave of triad-related crimes began early Wednesday
morning when three or four masked gunmen shot into the lounge of a
 newly-opened hotel with automatic rifles, injuring three people
including one security guard.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Portuguese News Agency Lusa reported that
Portuguese President Jorge Sampaio said during a visit to South
Africa on Wednesday that Macao's organized crimes must be dealt
with as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the worsening security situation in
Macao must be resolved quickly, and effective measures should be
taken.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all local Chinese newspapers in Macao carried editorials
 today, urging the government to take concrete and effective
measures to fight rising organized crimes in Macao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
