<HEADLINE> India's Bihar State Observes Strike Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- A dawn-to-dusk strike in
India's eastern Bihar state today disrupted normal life in the
whole state.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that the strike was called by
recently floated Rashtriya Janata Dal with former Bihar chief
minister Laloo Prasad Yadav as its president. The new party is a
faction split from the Janata Dal, the main constituent of the
ruing United Front in the center.
</P>
<P>
The strike was in protest against the alleged "false
implication" of its president, Laloo Prasad, in the multi-crore
fodder scam case.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) decided to prosecute
56 persons including Laloo Prasad on April 27 this year in
connection with the fodder scam.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the Supreme Court rejected Laloo's appeal for
anticipatory bail on July 29, the CBI headquarters directed to
execute the arrest warrant issued by the designated court on July
25 when Laloo Prasad resigned from chief ministership.
</P>
<P>
In the following day, Laloo surrendered before the CBI
designated court. He told his supporters that he would be proved
to be innocent in the fodder scam case.
</P>
<P>
Aggressive Laloo Prasad supporters today blocked roads and
railway tracks in the state. Party activists, armed with laths and
swords, took to the streets shouting slogans against the CBI for
falsely implicating the former chief minister, Laloo Prasad, in
the fodder scam.
</P>
<P>
All modes of transport were badly hit throughout the state as
strike supporters squatted on roads and railway lines disrupting
movement of traffic at several places. Shops and business
establishments downed shutters in most major townships.  
</P>
</TEXT>
