<HEADLINE> African Women Vow to Fight for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Assetu Koite, Secretary-General
of Pan African Women's Organisation (PAWO), pledged on Thursday
to support existing mechanism aimed at resolving conflicts on
troubled spots in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The PAWO, formed in 1962 to fight against colonialism, has now
shifted its focus on regional conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at the close of the Eighth PAWO
Conference here, Koite said women delegations would be sent to
talk to warring factions in an attempt to amicably resolve
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The PAWO would also collaborate with the recently-formed First
Ladies' Club of the Organisation of African Unity as they had the
same mission, she said.
</P>
<P>
Koite said the PAWO would try to help countries such as Libya
who were facing sanctions. It was often the women and children
who suffered as a result of these, she added.
</P>
<P>
''African women have an important role to play in this because
without peace there is no development and therefore no women's
intergration,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
The organisation would also work towards eliminating
illiteracy, poverty and other problems facing women, she said.
</P>
<P>
The theme for this year's PAWO conference was, ''Conflicts in
Africa, from Rhetoric to Action''.
</P>
<P>
The conference started on July 28 had focused its discussions
</P>
<P>
on issues concerning poverty, education, violence, economic
empowerment and status of women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
