<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Extends Smoking Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Singapore said today that
smoking ban in the country will be extended starting from August
15, in order to protect non-smokers from second hand smoke.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Environment said that the smoking ban will be
extended to cover schools, private clubs and all air-conditioned
shops from August 15.
</P>
<P>
It said that the extension of smoking prohibition to these new
areas will further protect non-smokers from the harmful effects of
second hand tobacco smoke. Government statistics show that 83
percent of the Singaporeans are non-smokers.
</P>
<P>
Under the extended ban, schools, junior colleges and institutes
of technical education and polytechnics will be made totally smoke
free. For universities, the prohibition will only apply to covered
buildings, regardless of whether it is air-conditioned or not.
</P>
<P>
Private clubs will also be included in the prohibition. Areas
affected by the ban are bowling alleys, billiard saloons and
arcade games rooms.
</P>
<P>
In addition, smoking in air-conditioned shops outside shopping
centers such as those in hotels, petrol stations and town centers
will also not be allowed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
