<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Share Market Closes Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
closed weaker today in uneventful trade, with some profit taking
and softer blue chips weighing upon the bourse.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones' Hamish Dee said the market closed on
a lower note this week with some profit-taking after the surprise
rate cut announcement by the Reserve Bank of Australia earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
Shaw Stockbroking's Michael Heffernan said it was a fairly
average finish to a busy week, inflated by a big move in Foster's
Brewing Group stock.
</P>
<P>
"It's about average but there was some portfolio buying... it
might be a little softer than normal," Heffernan said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished 7.6 points down at 2,727.5,
after trading in a 13 point range today.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 387.36 million shares traded with a value
of 906.39 million Australian dollars (670.72 million US dollars).
Rises of 527 outnumbered falls of 506.
</P>
<P>
Among the majors, Foster's Brewing Group was one of the most
heaviest traded stocks with turnover of 22.865 million shares
valued at 43.882 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
At the close, shares in Foster's were down 1.8 Australian cents
at 2.61 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
"I think the volume is a combination of a little Foster's
buyback activity," a broker said.
</P>
<P>
Last week Foster's shareholders voted to proceed with a 462.5
million US dollar share buyback deal with Japanese brewer Asahi.
</P>
<P>
The buyback of 254.5 million shares will be made at a price of
2.46 Australian dollars per share.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was down 9.2 points to 1,434.7, while
the all industrials index closed 6.4 points weaker at 4,386.1.
</P>
<P>
Market heavyweights BHP, WMC and Rio Tinto had all suffered a
drop in price.
</P>
<P>
BHP was down 23 cents at 18.01 Australian dollars on turnover
of 3.42 million shares, WMC fell 14.6 cents to 7.64 Australian
dollars and Rio Tinto lost 8.4 cents to 20.793 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the bank sector, National Australia Bank fell three cents to
19.51 Australian dollars, Westpac Banking Corp dropped 12.3 to
8.62 Australian dollars, ANZ was down three at 10.70 Australian
dollars and Commonwealth Bank of Australia remained steady at
16.65 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
St George Bank shot up 21 cents to 8.95 Australian dollars in
the wake of the rate cut, a move Heffernan attributed to a general
review of the bank yields being conducted by brokers.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was up 12 points to 1,337.9.
</P>
<P>
Spot gold bullion was trading in Sydney at 324.55 US dollars an
ounce this evening, down from 326.50 US dollars at Thursday's
close.  
</P>
</TEXT>
