<HEADLINE> More Foreign Investment For Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province, a traditional
industrial base in northeast China, is a new spot for foreign
investment, says Governor Wen Shizhen, speaking about economic
co-operation with Canada.
</P>
<P>
Although Canadian investment in Liaoning is still small, it has
been increasing in recent years and was up to 200 million US
dollars in 1996. Some 38 Canadian-funded ventures were set up in
1996, and trade with Canada was worth 84 million US dollars last
year, twice the 1994 figure.
</P>
<P>
Wen attributed the growth in investment to the province's
location in the center of the Northeast Asian Economic Zone and
importance as a passageway for inland areas. It also has a tenth
of China's large and medium-sized metallurgy, petrochemical,
electro-mechanical, and petroleum industries.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has built a road, railway, airline, and marine
transport web, leading other provinces in the number of railways,
and has 40 international and domestic air routes.
</P>
<P>
The central government has developed a series of preferential
policies for industrial enterprise reforms, providing more
opportunities for co-operation with the outside world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
