<HEADLINE> Fontaine, Stone Win Opening round of World Cup Ski </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- World champion Nicolas Fontaine
of Canada and Nikki Stone of the United States won their
respective events in the first round of the World Cup freestyle
skiing competition in Mt Buller, Australia on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Events at the first ever Australian round of a World Cup
freestyle event were overshadowed by Wednesday's disaster at
Thredbo where up to 20 people went missing in a landslide.
</P>
<P>
Fontaine dominated the men's section, scoring 238.89 followed
by American Matt Chojnacki with 235.18 and Canada's Andy Capicik
with 233.40.
</P>
<P>
Stone, the 1995 World Cup winner, was successful with a
full-double-full routine for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Canadians Veronica Brenner (174.48) and Caroline Olivier
(170.35) took the silver and bronze respectively.
</P>
<P>
Australia's world champion Kirstie Marshall finished fourth.
</P>
<P>
For the first time ever in a World Cup, Australian eucalyptus
gum leaves were thrown onto the landing area rather than the
northern hemisphere pine needles.
</P>
<P>
The leaves give the aerialists a contrast to the snow and an
indication of where the ground is as they twist and turn through
the air. 
</P>
</TEXT>
