<HEADLINE> 350 Cars Stolen in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 1 (Xinhua) -- About 350 cars were stolen in
Zimbabwe during the first five months of this year, the local
daily ''Herald'' reported today.
</P>
<P>
This means that about three cars are stolen every day, said
the report, adding that others are broken into and vandalised or
have valuables removed while some vehicles have been recovered.
</P>
<P>
While some of the thefts were unavoidable, police feel that
some could have been avoided, had the owners properly secured
their vehicles, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It was important for owners to ensure that their vehicles were
fitted with functional and secure locks in addition to alarms and
immobiliser systems, said the report quoting police officer
Comm Mpofu.
</P>
<P>
''Security is expensive but not foolproof. It is important to
have more than one system. This will make the job of the thief
more difficult,'' the police officer added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
