<HEADLINE> American Irrigation Technology Helping Farming In NW China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Irrigation technology from the
United States has proven effective in northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region for saving water, preventing diseases and
pests, and increasing crop output.
</P>
<P>
The region has been making an effort to become the country's
largest cotton producer and a major grain producer, but its dry
climate and lack of water are obstacles. So it spent more than 400
million yuan on water-saving agriculture, better canals, and the
new technology of drip irrigation, which is better than sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
Trial use in Turpan and Shihezi this spring showed that the new
method uses two-thirds less water than the traditional canal
irrigation, and reduced weeds, diseases, and pests at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
"Farmers in the trial project areas have seen the difference of
the two irrigation methods, and have begun voluntarily to adapt
themselves to the new technology and modern agriculture," said
Dr. Menqi, associate research fellow at the Xinjiang Academy of
Agricultural Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The region now uses more than 3,000 cubic meters of water less
per-ha of farmland than in the 1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
