<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Uses Gene Therapy on Hurler Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- A British baby girl Thursday
became the world's first person to be given gene therapy for her
rare inherited Hurler disease, The Daily Telegraph reported here
today.
</P>
<P>
The 15-month-old girl has Hurler disease which can cause an
essential protein missing and building waste products in
cells. The children with the disease often develop a range of
physical and mental problems and do not often survive beyond the
age of 10.
</P>
<P>
The transfusion of modified bone marrow back into her body took
about an hour at Royal Manchester Children's Hospital. Last week,
the baby's bone marrow cells were removed and then modified at the
Paterson Institute, at the Christie Hospital, in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
The cells were put in contact with a virus containing a normal
gene. This was repeated over five days and the cells were returned
into the baby via a large vein. The normal gene should instruct
the baby's cells to make the missing protein and prevent the
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
In about six months, doctors will know if the transfer is
working and the girl is functioning normally.
</P>
<P>
"We emphasize that this is an experiment. We have shown it is
possible to do this in a laboratory using bone marrow cultures
from Hurler patients," said a spokesman for the Royal Manchester
Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first attempt to do this in a patient. It is
likely we will get more questions than answers from this
attempt. We are taking the very first steps down a long road
toward finding an effective treatment for this disease and others
like it," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970801.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Stock Index Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Composite Stock Index on the
Shanghai Stock Exchange finished at 1,192.82 today, up 3.06 points
from the previous closing, according to the Guangfa Securities
Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
