<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Pakistan Sign Cooperation Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Pakistan today
agreed to strengthen their bilateral ties and signed two documents
on cooperation in economic and defense fields.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Malaysian Inno-Enhance Private Limited and
Pakistan's Punjab government and the Punjab Industrial Board
signed an agreement on setting up an export-processing zone in
Pakistan.
The agreement was signed after talks between Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad and his Pakistani counterpart Nawaz
Sharif, who arrived here on Thursday for a four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Two countries also signed a memorandum of understanding on
defense cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi told reporters
after the talks between the two prime ministers that defense was a
new field of cooperation between the two countries, which could
include training of officers and possibly cooperation in defense
industry.
</P>
<P>
Badawi said the two prime ministers agreed during their talks
that bilateral cooperation should be further expanded in the
fields of science and technology, education and defense.
Mahathir offered during the talks to share with Pakistan
Malaysia's experience in privatization, Badawi said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani officials would be offered facilities to attend
relevant courses in Malaysia, Badawi said.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan is interested to learn from us the various aspects
relating to privatization as we have vast experience in the
field," Badawi said.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers also discussed regional issues in their
talks, Badawi said.
</P>
<P>
On Kashmir, Badawi said that Mahathir lauded the initiative by
Pakistan and India to hold talks to resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
On Afghanistan, both leaders expressed the hope that political
stability would return there so that development could take place,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
