<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Export Control Regulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The 61st meeting of the State
Council Executive Committee, chaired by Premier Li Peng, ended
today with China's highest governing body passing in principle
three draft regulations, including a regulation on the control of
nuclear exports.
</P>
<P>
Additional regulations cover the administration of radio and
television shows, and other commercial performances.
</P>
<P>
Committee members stressed the necessity for formulating the
nuclear export control regulation to safeguard national security
and public interests, as well as promote international cooperation
in the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
Said regulation consists of 22 clauses, and an accompanying
annex listing nuclear exports subject to control.
</P>
<P>
China joined the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty in 1992 and in
May 1996 made its commitment to refrain from providing assistance
to nuclear facilities beyond the guarantees and monitoring of the
International Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
The aforementioned administrative regulation addresses problems
arising in the respective areas.
</P>
<P>
The draft regulation on the administration of radio and
televisions consists of 56 articles in six chapters, with the
commercial performances regulation containing 55 articles in five
chapters.
</P>
<P>
Revised drafts of the three regulations will be presented to
the State Council for promulgation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
