<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Construction Codes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The earthquake-prone Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region recently made public construction codes
for earthquake resistant buildings.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations require earthquake resistant designs and
building materials for new buildings, both civil and industrial
structures.
</P>
<P>
Strong earthquakes have been recorded throughout the region in
recent years, with seven quakes measuring at least 6 on the
Richter Scale hitting Jiashi County in the first four months of
this year alone. Said quakes resulted in severe casualties and
heavy damage which expert attribute to collapsing buildings.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang seismologists have created two seismic zone intensity
maps since the 1970s, and related regional departments have
completed in-depth appraisals of the Urumqi Petrochemical Works,
the Dushanzi Ethylene Plants, main railways and various other
major projects.
</P>
<P>
The region has reinforced buildings in 32 cities and counties
and has introduced stringent earthquake prediction
procedures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970801.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU First Quarter Exports Up 9.9% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 1 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU)'s exports
with the rest of the world rose by 9.9 percent in the
January-March period to 158.6 billion ECUs (about 170.2 billion
U.S. dollars), said today's issue of the European Report.
</P>
<P>
The Eurostat, EU's statistics arm, described the growth as
"dynamic" compared to the 4-percent export growth registered
during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
"It is the 12th positive quarter in a row," Eurostat said.
</P>
<P>
The growth in exports was particularly strong in Britain (up
26.2 percent), Ireland (17.5 percent) and Belgium-Luxembourg (16.5
percent).
</P>
<P>
Imports into EU countries were also on the rise as Eurostat
figures showed a solid increase of 8.4 percent to 155.1 billion
ECUs (about 166.5 billion dollars) as against the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Britain had the biggest rise of imports at 16.3 percent,
followed by France with 12.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The European Report, a mouthpiece of EU's executive body the
European Commission, quoted Eurostat as saying that it is in line
with the 1995 and 1996 trend of remarkable extra EU surpluses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
