<HEADLINE> African Women's Day Celebrated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 1 (Xinhua) -- African women celebrated the
African Women's Day here on thursday amid calls for peace and
stability on the continent.
</P>
<P>
In solidarity messages at the celebrations which coincided
with the closing of the eighth Pan African Women's Organisation
(PAWO) congress which started on July 28, the attendants urged
leaders to bring an end to the wars which had brought sufferings
to African women and children.
</P>
<P>
''We are tired of wars, hatred and intolerance which is
abundant in our men who left us in a state of misery,'' said
Filomena Delgado, Angolan Deputy Minister of Women's Affairs.
''We would like to see peace so that we can fight for economic
development with practical strategies," she added.
</P>
<P>
Delgado urged African factional leaders to transform their
guns into hoes to cultivate land and to channel their energies
towards developing their countries.
</P>
<P>
She stressed the need African governments to reconstruct
their economies and invest in training to enhance productivity.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan deputy minister also urged African governments to
implement the resolutions reached at the PAWO congress.
</P>
<P>
Other representatives speaking at the meeting called on
African women to continue their fight against oppression of women
as they had did in the struggle against colonialism in the past.
</P>
<P>
July 31 was declared the Aafrican Women's Day by the
Organisation of African Unity to enable women to reflect on their
successes and failures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
