<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Identity Cards to Be Issued in S.Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will issue new
identity cards containing the name, photograph, and fingerprint
of a citizen to replace the present book-like identity documents,
local daily The Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
Provision for the credit-card size ID cards is made in a new
Identification Bill, introduced by Home Affairs Minister
Mangosuthu Buthelezi.
</P>
<P>
The future ID cards will be machine-readable, similar to
present automatic teller machine (ATM) cards.
</P>
<P>
The concept of the card is ''to ensure an efficient identity
verification service'' to any department of state, business house
or insurance company, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The cards would also provide sufficient security features to
ensure they cannot be forged or counterfeited, and that they
resist damage, Buthelezi was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Existing identity documents will remain valid until people
have obtained new identity cards, or a date is promulgated for
the expiry of the old identity documents, the report added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
