<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian President in Tehran on Unexpected Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani and the visiting Syrian President Hafiz Al-Assad have
stressed the need for safeguarding Iraq's territorial integrity,
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported early this morning.
</P>
<P>
Hafiz Al-Assad arrived in Tehran for a unexpected state visit
Thursday. This is his second visit to Iran since the Iranian
Islamic revolution in 1979. His last came to Tehran in 1990.
</P>
<P>
As reports say that Tehran, Damascus and Baghdad are trying to
form a block in confrontation with the Israeli-Turkish military
alliance, Al-Assad's visit has drawn wide international attention.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian and Syrian presidents held the first round of talks
here Thursday focusing on the bilateral relations and the issue of
Iraq. However, IRNA gave no details on what Iran and Syria are
trying to do on the issue of Iraq and what kind of military
cooperation they are going to forge ahead to confront the military
cooperation between Turkey and Israel.
</P>
<P>
According to IRNA, the presidents of Iran and Syria had
exchanged their views for broadening regional cooperation between
the two strategic allies, for the ouster of foreign troops in the
Persian Gulf, for supporting the righteous cause and struggle of
the people of Palestine, and for closer collaboration between
Muslim nations.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani told Syrian president that Iran and Syria are two
important Muslim nations of the region, and that closer relations
and cooperation between them would contribute to peace and
stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran is to uphold her original position in
relation with the issue of Palestine and stressed the need for
struggling against the Israeli regime.
</P>
<P>
"Iran greatly values her friendship with Syria," he was quoted
by the IRNA report as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president said that the issue of Jerusalem was a
strategic one as far as Iran was concerned.
</P>
<P>
He added that in dealing with that issue Syria had acted more
responsibly than other Arab and Muslim governments.
</P>
<P>
"To establish or broaden relations with Muslim and Arab
governments that face the challenges of the international
arrogance and the Zionist regime more boldly than others is a
basic consideration in the principles of Iran's foreign policy,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Hafiz Al-Assad was quoted by the report as saying that
relations between the two countries were at their best in every
respect, and observed that his government was committed to
further broadening relations with Iran in the area of politics,
economy and culture.
</P>
<P>
Syrian President Hafiz Al-Assad also appreciated Iran's
regional policy which, he said, was for peace and stability, and
good neighborly relations with all her neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970801.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
