<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 07:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel To Uproot Hamas Infrastructure In West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 1 (Xinhua) -- In a move that may have
dangerous religious implications, the Israeli government has
decided to destroy the infrastructure of the Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas) in the West Bank, according to a report of the
state-run Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed security source was quoted by the radio as saying
that the Ministerial Committee on National Security, known as
inner security cabinet, had given the security forces the
go-ahead to operate against the civil infrastructure of Hamas in
Area B of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement between Israel and the Palestinians signed
in 1995, during the interim period, the West Bank was divided into
Area A, Area B and Area C. Area B is under Palestinian civil
administration, but Israel still maintains overriding security
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The move was apparently part of the steps taken by the inner
security cabinet which met in an emergency session late Wednesday
night in the wake of the double suicide bombing attack in the
central open market of Jerusalem, which killed 13 Israelis and
wounded 168.
</P>
<P>
The security source said that actions could be taken, for
example, against Islamic charity funds and Mosques.
</P>
<P>
According to a cabinet communique issued at the end of the
inner security cabinet meeting, the army and security services
were ordered to carry out "a series of security measures against
the Palestinian terrorist organizations."
</P>
<P>
According to the radio report, some of the security measures
have aroused deep concerns of international human right
organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970801.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Biography of Dunhuang Caves Scholar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, August 1 (Xinhua) -- A recently released biography
authored by Luo Qingzhi portrays the life of well-known scholar
Duan Wenjie and explains legends of the Dunhuang Caves.
</P>
<P>
The young author spent three years researching historical
materials and writing the 280,000-word book.
</P>
<P>
Duan, director of Dunhuang Research Institute in northwest
China's Gansu Province, has studied Dunhuang paintings and
conducted related intensive research since 1946.
</P>
<P>
The octogenarian scholar has copied numerous Dunhuang frescoes
throughout a long career filled with notable academic achievements.
</P>
<P>
Duan has dedicated himself to ensuring that Chinese specialists
equal the great academic achievements overseas experts have
recorded in the field of Dunhuang research.
</P>
<P>
The Dunhuang Caves, which date back as far back as 366,
house invaluable Buddhist statues, frescos and manuscripts.
</P>
<P>
The author retains his focus on Duan, while at the same time
describing the historical activities of other famous Dunhuang
scholars. Luo objectively depicts controversial figures, such as a
 Taoist priest named Wang who is traditionally regarded as a
traitor for selling cultural relics to foreign collectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
