<DOCNO> XIE19970801.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fruit Trees Benefit Chinese Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in mountainous parts of
China's Shanxi Province in north China have made life better with
a fruit tree program the provincial government started in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The farmers' efforts paid off, giving Shanxi a good part of the
domestic market, and access to more than 20 countries and regions
as well.
</P>
<P>
Some 660,000 ha of fruit trees in the province provide 1.8
billion kg of fruit annually, 50 kg per capita more than the
national average.
</P>
<P>
"We will double the acreage to 1.33 million ha by the end of
the century, to give every farmer a 15th of a ha of fruit
trees," said Wang Wenxue, deputy governor for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Five fruit-growing bases have taken shape and produce over 70
percent of the province's total fruit output.
</P>
<P>
Mountainous Luliang Prefecture is one example, with some
430,000 households in 1,100 poor villages having improved their
lives a great deal by growing jujubes, walnuts, and Chinese
prickly ash.
</P>
<P>
Yuncheng Prefecture is another example, with 300,000 ha of
fruit trees that put 400 more yuan in the pockets of each of three
million farmers annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
