<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relying On Science For Economic Growth In NW China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Underdeveloped parts of China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region are making the most of science
and technology for economic growth to narrow the east-west gap.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, it adopted this strategy, and by 1996, spending on
science and technology was 77.5 percent more than in 1992. The
region has completed 1,293 research projects in the past five
years, with science and technology contributing 35 percent to
local economic growth, according to the regional Science and
Technology Commission.
</P>
<P>
It has also increased co-operation overseas and has sent
several hundred scholars abroad for further study and research.
</P>
<P>
Some large research projects, such as a mineral resources
exploitation project, a Tarim desert highway, and a cotton
research project have greatly helped local progress and have
helped train scientists.
</P>
<P>
Science and technology departments have begun to provide
technical assistance to improve enterprises and have set up more
than 1,000 information service centers in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang has finished 56 of a planned 133 science and
technology projects, involving 25 million yuan in investment and
nearly a billion yuan of capital from other sectors. The projects
added 2.36 billion yuan in output value and 630 million yuan in
pre-tax profits.
</P>
<P>
A 330,000-ha high-yield grain project has raised per-ha output
from 280 kg to more than 400 kg, adding one billion kg of grain.
</P>
