<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 07:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Troops Arrest 50 Palestinian Extremists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli security forces have
arrested 50 Palestinian extremist activists overnight in the
crackdown on terrorism in the wake of Wednesday's suicide
bombing attacks in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the operations were carried out by
Israeli troops in the areas in the territories under Israeli
control.
</P>
<P>
Despite Israeli government's decision to authorize its troops
to enter the PNA (Palestinian National Authority) self-rule areas
to arrest terrorists, Israeli soldiers so far have not entered
these areas.
</P>
<P>
The arrested were from the militant Islamic Jihad and Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas), which carried out the twin bombings
Wednesday in central Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda free market,
killing 15 people and wounding over 170 others.
</P>
<P>
Under Israel's pressure, Palestinian police have also arrested
a number of extremists from Hamas and Islamic Jihad.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli security forces were put on high alert amid
warnings about more terror attacks. Police reinforcements were
deployed in Jerusalem and Tel Aviv, which is another popular
target for terrorists. Hundreds of policemen were stationed in Tel
Aviv's beach area and roadblocks have been erected at entrances to
the city.
</P>
<P>
The United States' Embassy to Israel in Tel Aviv has issued
warning to U.S. citizens to take precautions against possible
terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
The closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip, imposed by
Israeli troops after the Wednesday terror bombings, has been
eased to allow the entry into Israel of Palestinian lawyers,
medical personnels and people who needed humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
But about 20 members of the Palestinian Council who concluded a
meeting in the West Bank city of Ramallah Thursday were refused
entry into Israel to travel back to Gaza.
</P>
<P>
To increase pressure on the PNA to fight terrorism, Israel has
transferred a list of suspected terrorists to the PNA, which was
asked to take tougher actions against not only the extremists, but
also the infrastructure that support them.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian police chief, Ghazi Jabali, who is among the
wanted list for alleged involvement in terrorism, laughed off the
Israeli demand to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
He told a news conference in Gaza Thursday that Israel could
not arrest him because it ran counter to the peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Jabali was charged by Israel for personally planning a terror
attack against a Jewish settlement near the West Bank city Nablus
last month. Israel said its soldiers arrested three Palestinian
policemen who were on their way to carry out the attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
