<HEADLINE> More Villages to Have Power Supply in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka hopes to supply
electricity to 1,000 villages covering 100,000 households by the
year 2000, Irrigation and Power Ministry sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The project under the rural electrification scheme will cost 60
million US dollars and the Asian Development Bank has already
provided a soft loan to Sri Lanka for this purpose, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, 80 percent of Sri Lanka's households
will have electricity by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Under a phased-out project 200 villages will be supplied with
electricity this year while 400 villages will get electricity in
1998 and another 400 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
To meet an annual increase in the demand for power, a master
plan has been prepared by Sri Lanka's Electricity Board. This will
be implemented in 1999 at a cost of 25 billion Rupees (423 million
US dollars) and will be completed in 2005.  
</P>
