<HEADLINE> Panama Hails Prospect of End to U.S. Tuna Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Panama today welcomed the
United States Senate's vote to lift its embargo on tuna imports
which has cost Latin American exporters some 600 million dollars a
year. .
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister for Commerce and Industries Jose Troyano said
today the move was very significant as the embargo had seriously
affected Panama, Colombia, Costa Rica, Mexico and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
"We feel satisfied, because Panama is one of the Central
American countries that has been struggling for this measure to be
reversed," Troyano said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate on Wednesday unanimously approved ending the
tuna embargo which was imposed in 1991 because of allegations that
dolphins were being killed in tuna fishing nets.
</P>
<P>
Panama does not have a tuna industry, but faced losses from a
big drop in services to tuna fishing ships that arrived in the
country to make transshipments.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposal to lift the embargo will now be sent to the
U.S. House of Representatives, which has supported the lifting,
and then to U.S. President Bill Clinton for promulgation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
