<HEADLINE> Nicaragua-Mexico Free Trade Agreement Almost Ready </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The free trade agreement between
Nicaragua and Mexico is almost ready with only differences of
imports of meat, sugar, dairy products and grain remaining,
Nicaragua's economics ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the agreement could be ready to sign in
September during Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman's visit to
Mexico, said Oscar Aleman, foreign trade director and negotiations
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
He said that on Tuesday Nicaragua and Mexico started a new
round of talks about the treaty focusing on access to markets,
agriculture, fresh food hygiene standards, services, copyright,
government acquisitions and unfair trade practices.
</P>
<P>
The main sticking points are in the drafting sections on
the agriculture and livestock sectors, where Mexico is concerned
about imports of meat, sugar, dairy products and grains.
</P>
<P>
"The free trade agreement should be seen as part of a process
of liberalization that cannot be reversed," said Aleman. 
</P>
