<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   International Conference on Albania's Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from 23 countries and 15
international organizations met here today to discuss economic
reconstruction in Albania after the country's June election put a
new government in place.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Italy, Britain, the United States, France,
Germany, the European Union (EU) and the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) studied the three-step political
and economic reconstruction scheme proposed by Albania's new
Prime Minister Fatos Nano.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agreed that the country's reconstruction could not
be carried out smoothly unless the new government and other
political forces were committed to national reconciliation and
sought closer cooperation with the international community.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE's special envoy to Albania, Franz Vranitzky, said
after the meeting that as Albania's situation is still
complicated, the parties concerned are preparing a "package plan"
to ensure there is no repetition of the unrest which engulfed
Albania in earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The collapse of shady pyramid saving schemes in January
triggered nationwide anarchy and brought about the downfall of
President Sali Berisha.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided to hold a donors' meeting next month in
Brussels, Belgium, to raise funds for the shattered Balkan
state. A ministerial meeting is also scheduled in September in
Rome to address Albania's medium-term reconstruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
