<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Law Begins To Rule Shanghai's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Huasheng Chemical
Industry Company started out 15 years ago with just nine
employees, three water vats and six sticks for mixing chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Now Huasheng is the country's largest paint-maker, with
per capita pre-tax profits of 730,000 yuan, ranking first among
all local firms in the city and even better than its international
competitors.
</P>
<P>
General Manager Li Longming attributes the success of his
company mainly to the market competition, which has forced the
firm to adopt a scientific approach to management.
</P>
<P>
Huasheng is only one of a large number of local enterprises
benefiting from the city's fledgling market economy, he says.
</P>
<P>
Competition, which is seen as the spice of the market economy,
has been playing an increasingly bigger role and created new
incentives for the economic development of China's largest
industrial city, some local experts say.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 43 local firms went bankrupt, bringing the total
number of bankrupt companies in Shanghai to 58. So far, 730 local
enterprises have been merged. And at least 50 large enterprise
groups have become big economic powers through capital expansion
and mergers in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a unified and open labor market system, with 437 job
agencies, has taken shape to form a market-led employment system
in the city. In 1996, 157,000 laid-off factory workers found work
through the labor market.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is the first city in China to forecast the market
demand for laborers.
</P>
<P>
As in other parts of China, the managers and directors of local
firms in Shanghai used to be appointed by higher-ups, but under
the market economy, head staffers must be hired for their merits.
</P>
<P>
The newly-founded Shanghai Factory Director and Manager Company
has a list of over 9,800 talent candidates for recommendation. The
year-old firm has found posts for 183 managerial-level job-seekers.
</P>
<P>
The market law has also accelerated the development of a social
security plan that protects all local employees and jobless people.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 6.15 million local employees and retirees, 95
percent of the city's total, are covered by the city's pension
system, while some 150,000 people have received cash from the
unemployment subsidiary fund, and another 120,000 people are
getting various forms of additional insurance.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, Shanghai has set bottom lines for the lowest living
standard, lowest income level, and numbers of unemployed and laid
off people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
