<HEADLINE> Canada Funds Health Care Project in Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The first health care project
sponsored by the Canadian Government in China has been launched in
Yunnan Province, southwest China, benefiting mothers and children
of ethnic minority groups in 10 poverty-stricken counties, local
official sources said.
</P>
<P>
Over the next four years, the Canada International Development
Agency (CIDA) will pour a total of six million Canadian dollars
(about 4.3 million US dollars) into the program, which is designed
to build medical facilities and bring trained workers to the rural
areas of the counties.
</P>
<P>
Among the 10 counties named in the project are the Naxi
Autonomous County of Lijiang, the Bai Autonomous Prefecture of
Dali, and the Dai Autonomous Prefecture of Xishuangbanna, with a
total population of 2.38 million.
</P>
<P>
The Yunnan provincial government will also provide an
additional 4.3 million dollars in funding, according to local
officials.
</P>
<P>
They say that each year in the counties, nine out of every
1,000 children under age five, and nearly two out of every 1,000
pregnant women die as a result of the shortage of medical
equipment and professional medical staff.  
</P>
</TEXT>
