<HEADLINE> Breastfeeding Campaigners Launch Activities in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Medics and workers involved in
maternal and child health care started a week-long publicity
campaign today to promote breastfeeding among new mothers through
out China.
</P>
<P>
The annual World Breastfeeding Week, an event launched by the
World Alliance for Breastfeeding Action (Waba), will be observed
in China and other 120-odd countries in the next seven days.
</P>
<P>
China's Ministry of Health (MOH) has issued a circular calling
for expanded publicity on breastfeeding this week so as to arouse
public concern and support to the drive, said a "China Daily"
report.
</P>
<P>
Medical workers at all levels are asked to go down to the
grassroots areas to give consultancy and carry out health services
for mothers and babies, it said.
</P>
<P>
Health departments in cooperation with market watchdogs will
take examinations over packaging, marketing of breast milk
substitutes as well as television advertisements for such products.
</P>
<P>
MOH has set a goal of 80 percent breastfeeding rate in China by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, China has set up 4,730 baby-friendly
hospitals, in which infants are given to mothers for breastfeeding
immediately after birth, and doctors and nurses teach mothers
about breastfeeding and baby care.
</P>
<P>
Natural immunoglobulins and special antibodies contained in
mother's milk are generally considered to be good to development
of newly-borns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
