<DOCNO> XIE19970801.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAAF to Reduce Doping Ban from 4 to 2 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The International Amateur
Athletics Federation has decided to reduce the doping ban from
four years to two after two hours of discussion at the 41st IAAF
Congress which closed here today.
</P>
<P>
The Congress voted to reduce the sanction for a first doping
offence for prohibited substances (like anabolic agents,
amphetamines, Peptide Hormones, cocaine etc) from four years to a
"mimimum of two years." The sanction for a second offence shall
be life.
</P>
<P>
Athletes who are currently suspended for four years may apply
to the IAAF Council for reinstatement after they have served two
years. They must supply evidence that they have undergone three
out-of-competition tests (at least four months apart) during the
final year of their suspension.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF Congress also voted to change the current 3-month
sanction for using substances (stimulant, narcotic analgesics
etc) to a Public Warning. The sanction for a second offence
shall be two years. Performances obtained by an athlete in a
competition in which he, or she, tests positive will be declared
invalid.
</P>
<P>
As a consequence of this decision, the Jamaican long jumper
James Beckford, 1996 Olympic silver medallist, will be allowed to
take part in the 6th World Athletics Championships here.
Beckford tested positive for a stimulant at the IAAF Grand Prix
meeting in Paris on June 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
