<HEADLINE> Canadian Company Begins CDMA Project In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Northern Telecom (Nortel),
Canada's leading telecommunications supplier, and China's Shaanxi
Province have reached an agreement on a new digital mobile
telephone network in Xi'an, the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the CDMA (code diversion multiple
accesses) network, which is seen as a hopeful substitute for the
present GSM (global service for mobile communications) mode, will
use Nortel's CDMA system, which includes a DMS-MTX mobile
switching machine, a base station controller, and 12 base stations.
</P>
<P>
According to the lastest issue of People's Posts and
Telecommunications News, the network's switching capacity will be
13,000 accesses in the initial phase, and 50,000 in the future.
</P>
<P>
China is now building a trial CDMA network in the cities of
Xi'an, Beijing and Guangzhou.  
</P>
</TEXT>
