<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four out of 10 Colombians Drink Unsafe Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- More than 14.3 million
Colombians, or 41 percent of the population, can't get clean
drinking water, a government study said today.
</P>
<P>
Only 40 percent of Colombia's 35.1 million people, or 14
million, have access to potable water, according to the study by
the General Comptrollership.
</P>
<P>
More than nine million people in the provinces of Atlantico,
Bolivar, Cordoba, Meta, Risaralda, and Valle del Cauca are
affected by water shortages or unsafe water.
</P>
<P>
Seven in every 10 cities do not take sewage treatment
measures, causing health problems for more than eight million
residents.
</P>
<P>
These poor sanitation conditions have fueled the spread of
cholera, amebiasis, typhoid fever, para-typhoid fever, and
poliomyelitis, the study said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
