<HEADLINE> Record High TV Coverage for World Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The 6th World Athletics
Championships will receive the greatest Television coverage of any
sports event ever with 212 countries and regions getting images
from the festival scheduled to be held here from August 1 to 10.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest news, a total of 170 countries and
regions have paid for the TV rights. A total of 137 countries
will be broadcasting the competition live.
</P>
<P>
Following the recent agreement with Colombia, Brazil and
Mexico, it is estimated that more than 3.3 billion people will
watch the championships on TV. The African continent will also
receive three hours of action every day, free of charge.
</P>
<P>
A total of 200 countries and regions have sent teams to the
event, making it the best attended sports competition in
history. Last year's Olympics had 197 participating teams and the
1995 World Championships had 191.
</P>
<P>
A new record total of 1,957 athletes will take part, 1,225 men
and 732 women. The previous record was 1,804.
</P>
<P>
Ticket sales have been even better than expected. The Opening
Ceremony at the Panathinaikon Stadium tomorrow is sold out and all
tickets have been sold for August 3, the day of the 100 meters
finals for men and women.
</P>
<P>
All these statistics demonstrate the great strength of the
IAAF World Championships. The event brings together, without
exception, the best athletes on earth after International Amateur
Athletics Federation issued the wild cards to the defending
champions.
</P>
<P>
According to the Organising Committee, the IAAF has issued a
special invitation to the Mayors of cities bidding for the 2004
Summer Olympics to attend the Championships.
</P>
<P>
Mayors of Athens, Buenos Aires, Cape Town, Rome and Stockholm
are expected to be presented at this most important single sports
event.
</P>
<P>
For the first time at the championships, awards will be
available for the medallists with winners taking $60,000, silver
winners getting $30,000 and bronze medallists taking $20,000. The
world record breakers will win $100,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
