<HEADLINE> Zelezny Wants to Cap World Title for Third Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Jan Zelezny of the Czech Republic,
two times Olympic and world champion in the men's javelin,
determines to defend his world title at the 6th World Athletics
Championships starting here tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
With a big aim in mind, the 31-year-old said he is ready, but
added that strong winds could produce either a world record throw
or a fatal failure.
</P>
<P>
"I came to Athens to win. I have finished my training well.
Of course, I love to win, but in athletics everything may
happen. I believe that a medal will go to the athlete who throws
the javelin further than 87 meters. A throw of around 90 meters
will probably win the gold medal," said Zelezny, who is holding
the world record of 98.48 meters.
</P>
<P>
"It is a big stadium that allows for strong winds and very
easily a good throw can break the world record or fail
completely," added the Czech who won the golds in the 1992 and
1996 Olympics plus world titles in 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Zelezny flang the year's best mark of 94.02 meters last
March. The first three best throws this season were produced by
him. The only person who beat the 90-meter barrier this year is
Boris Henry of Germany, who managed a 90.44m performance early
this month.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the Greek champion Kostas Gatsioudis, who ranks
third best on the season's list with a 89.22m effort, Zelezny
commented: "He is a young and strong athlete, but he is only one
of the opponents I have to face. Sergey Makarov of Russia and
Steve Backley of Britain are the most dangerous threats."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
