<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Stumbles But Most Stock Indexes Set New Highs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial average
slipped from its record high Thursday, but most popular stock
measures set new highs again as interest rates hit another
17-month low in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow fell 32.28 to 8,222.61. It was weighed down by a report
confirming that the business activity slowed considerably in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department reported in the morning that the gross
domestic product expanded at a moderate 2.2 percent annual rate in
the second quarter as consumers grew more cautious after a
first-quarter spending spree that threatened to aggravate
inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
The government agency also revised its first-quarter GDP
reading downward to a still-vigorous 4.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
More important than the weekly employment tally, however, will
be Friday's reading on July payroll and wage levels, two key
factors behind inflation.
</P>
<P>
As bonds rose Thursday, the yield on the 30-year Treasury
dropped from late Wednesday's 6.32 percent, which was the lowest
finish since February 1996, to 6.29 percent.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume was heavy again at
547.87 million shares, down slightly from Wednesday's busy pace.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 2.00 to 954.29, and
the NYSE composite index rose 0.93 to 494.50, the third
consecutive record highs for both measures.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index closed at a record high for the
second day in a row, rising 5.76 to 1,593.81, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 0.98 to 646.30, its fourth
straight record finish.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
