<HEADLINE> U.S. House Approves Tax Cuts Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives today approved a package of tax cuts after the
Senate passed a bill to balance the budget and shrink the size of
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
The House approved the tax cut at mid-afternoon on a lopsided
vote of 389-43 and sent it to the Senate, which is expected to
vote on it on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the Senate passed by a bipartisan vote of
85-15 the budget-balance bill which was oked by the House on
Wednesday. The bill will be sent to President Bill Clinton for
signature.
</P>
<P>
The bill called for about 130 billion U.S. dollars in spending
restraint needed to balance the budget by the year of 2002.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the measure remodels Medicare and creates a new 24
billion U.S. dollars program of health care for uninsured children
insisted on by the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Clinton called the budget bill "the
achievement of a generation and a triumph for every American,"
adding that it marks an end to decades of deficits.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the bill is "the achievement of generation and
a triumph for every American," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"This good for America," said Senate Republican Leader Trent
Lott. "It's a major step forward. Maybe not a leap, but a major
step."
</P>
<P>
The balanced budget bill, a measure designed to rid the nation
of deficits for the first time since 1969, had held center stage
in both the Senate and the House.
</P>
<P>
Late in 1995, the dispute between the GOP and the Democrats
over the issue led to shutdowns of the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
