<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Rejects Libyan Offer on Pam Am Explosion Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Thursday
rejected an offer from Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi on a possible
settlement of the 1988 Pan Am flight 103 explosion by an
international entity.
</P>
<P>
Gadhafi's latest offer was contained in a letter, sent in June
to the families of the 270 victims. The letter said Libya was
ready to cooperate with the United States and Britain if they
accept any of the initiatives put forward by the "League of Arab
States, the Organization of African Unity or the Non-Aligned
Movement," or if they follow the more cooperative route of France.
</P>
<P>
The letter also said: "the government of the United States is
neither interested in the incident nor does it care about the
victims. Its main preoccupation has centered around the imposition
of sanctions against Libya."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno, flatly rejecting the offer,
said it was "a callous offer... to prey on the emotions of the
families in an attempt to undercut our will to see that justice is
served. We will not be manipulated like that."
</P>
<P>
The United States believes the two Libyan suspects, who set the
bomb that destroyed the airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, in
1988, killing 270 people, are still protected in Libya.
</P>
<P>
Attached to the letter were several offers from Libya: Accept
trial of the two suspects in a third country determined by the
U.N. Security Council, or trial under Scottish judges and law at
the Hague, or trial under a special criminal tribunal at the
Hague.
</P>
<P>
But Reno said the U.S. position was a trial in the United
States or in Britain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
