<HEADLINE> Clinton Nominates Air Force Chief of Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today nominated Gen. Michael Ryan, commander of U.S. Air Force in
Europe, as Air Force Chief of Staff to replace Gen. Ronald
Fogleman.
</P>
<P>
Ryan, a former fighter pilot who flew combat missions over
Vietnam, also holds the post of commander of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) air force in central Europe based in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
He had coordinated the air strikes on the Bosnian Serbs two
years ago to drive the Serbs to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Fogleman submitted his resignation Monday, saying that he
felt "out of step" with the Pentagon leadership.
</P>
<P>
However, he resigned partly because of his anticipation of a
decision by Defense Secretary William Cohen to hold another air
force general, Terryl Schwalier, responsible for failing to
protect against a truck bomb that killed 19 U.S. airmen in Saudi
Arabia last year.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said he was blocking the promotion of Schwalier since he
failed to prepare for possible bomb attack against the U.S. in
Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
